</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph pageId="73" pageNumber="74">
Note that in Dominican Republic a pubescent morphotype of 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia superba" order="Myrtales" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="superba">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">Conostegia superba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been collected in the same place. They are similar but when looking at the flower buds, 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia lindenii" order="Myrtales" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lindenii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">Conostegia lindenii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has pubescent buds with the lobes somewhat evident in the calyptra apex. In 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia superba" order="Myrtales" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="superba">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">Conostegia superba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on the other hand, the flower bud and calyptra are glabrous and the lobes not discernible at all.
</paragraph>
